{"descriptions":[{"id":1445,"title":"Böngya Tsokré Introduction","content":"\u003cdiv class=\"essay-body\"\u003e\u003cdiv id=\"essay-head2\"\u003e\u003ctable\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\u003ctd align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"\u003e\u003cdiv class=\"chapter\"\u003e\u003cem\u003eA Survey of Bonpo Monasteries\u003c/em\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003cdiv class=\"author\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"eng\"\u003eby \u003c/span\u003eDondrup Lhagyal, \n\t\tPhuntso Tsering Sharyul, \n\t\tTsering Thar, \n\t\tCharles Ramble and Marietta Kind\u003c!--(l)--\u003e\u003cbr/\u003eEdited by Samten G. Karmay and Yasuhiko Nagano \u003c/div\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd style=\"width: 100%; text-align: right;\" align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\u003e\u003cdiv class=\"copyright\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"eng\"\u003e Copyright \u0026copy; 2003. \u003c/span\u003e\u003cdiv class=\"eng\" id=\"permission\"\u003eReproduced with permission from the authors \u003cbr xmlns:str=\"http://exslt.org/strings\"/\u003eunder the \u003ca href=\"/tools/licenses.php#essay=/thl/text-license/\" class=\"thl-poplink\"\u003eTHL Digital Text License\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/div\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\u003c/tr\u003e\u003c/table\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003ch2 id=\"b6-4\"\u003eBonpo temples in sTong che\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n                  \u003ch3 id=\"b6-4-4\"\u003e(130) Bon brgya Tshogs ras (Tent Temple)\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n                  \u003cp\u003eTshogs ras signifies \u0026lsquo;cloth tent for gathering\u0026rsquo;.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n                  \u003cp\u003eIn Amdo dialect, the \u003cspan xmlns:str=\"http://exslt.org/strings\" style=\"font-style: italic;\" class=\"\"\u003esbra\u003c/span\u003e, \u0026lsquo;tent\u0026rsquo; is pronounced as \u0026lsquo;\u003cspan xmlns:str=\"http://exslt.org/strings\" style=\"font-style: italic;\" class=\"\"\u003era\u003c/span\u003e\u0026rsquo;, so that \u003cspan xmlns:str=\"http://exslt.org/strings\" style=\"font-style: italic;\" class=\"\"\u003etshogs sbra\u003c/span\u003e has become\n                        \u003cspan xmlns:str=\"http://exslt.org/strings\" style=\"font-style: italic;\" class=\"\"\u003etshogs ras\u003c/span\u003e since the tent is now made of cotton.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n                  \u003cp\u003eBon brgya Tshogs ras is one of the very few tent temples that is still used in\n                     Amdo. The Tent Temple has no fixed location. It is moved from one place to\n                     another just as the nomadic tents. Every year a new location for the tent is\n                     chosen to perform the annual rituals. These rituals are usually performed only\n                     in autumn on pasture so that the weather is still warm and convenient for the\n                     people to attend the ceremony. \u003c/p\u003e\n\n               \u003ctable xmlns:str=\"http://exslt.org/strings\" cellspacing=\"8\" align=\"center\" class=\"navarrows\"\u003e\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\u003ctd class=\"leftcell\"\u003e\u003ca class=\"backarrow\" title=\"Previous Section\"\u003e\u003cimg src=\"/global/images/arrow-left.gif\" title=\"Previous Section\"/\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd class=\"midcell\"\u003e\u003ca class=\"uparrow\" title=\"Beginning of Article\"\u003e\u003cimg src=\"/global/images/arrow-up.gif\" title=\"Beginning of Article\"/\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd class=\"rightcell\"\u003e\u003ca class=\"forwardarrow\" title=\"Next Section\"\u003e\u003cimg src=\"/global/images/arrow-right.gif\" title=\"Next Section\"/\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\u003c/tr\u003e\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003cdiv id=\"chap-id\"\u003e/bonpo-monasteries/b6-4-4/\u003c/div\u003e\u003cdiv style=\"overflow: hidden; height: 300px;\" class=\"jqmWindow\" id=\"chapRefWindow\"\u003e\u003cdiv class=\"closebtn\"\u003e\u003ca href=\"#\"\u003eClose\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003cdiv style=\"height: 280px;\" class=\"conx-content\"\u003e\u003ch3\u003eNote Citation for Page \u003cspan class=\"pgnm\"/\u003e\u003c/h3\u003e\u003cp class=\"biblref\"\u003eDondrup Lhagyal, Phuntso Tsering Sharyul, Tsering Thar, Charles Ramble, and \n\t\tMarietta Kind, A Survey of Bonpo Monasteries and Temples in\n               Tibet and the Himalaya\n\t\t\t\t(ISBN: ,\t\n\t\t\t\t:, \n\t\t\t\t2010-07-06), \n\t\t\t\t\u003cspan class=\"pgnm\"/\u003e.\n\t\t\t\u003c/p\u003e\u003ch3\u003eBibliographic Citation\u003c/h3\u003e\u003cp\u003eDondrup Lhagyal, Phuntso Tsering Sharyul, Tsering Thar, Charles Ramble, and \n\t\tMarietta Kind. A Survey of Bonpo Monasteries and Temples in\n               Tibet and the Himalaya, . \n\t\t\t\t(ISBN:\\)\t:, 2010-07-06.\u003c/p\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003c/div\u003e","source_url":"/places/monasteries/publications/bon-book.php#!book=/bonpo-monasteries/wb/b6-4-4","is_primary":false,"created_at":"2011-12-13 02:29:49 UTC","updated_at":"2011-12-13 02:29:49 UTC","authors":[{"id":"80","fullname":"ཚེ་རིང་ཐར། (Tsering Thar)"},{"id":"80","fullname":"ཚེ་རིང་ཐར། (Tsering Thar)"}]}]}